The paper discusses Grid protocols that facilitate coordinated resource sharing across diverse organizations, which falls under the category of Distributed Computing (cs.DC). The paper also covers network communication, data transfer, information security, resource information, management, and interface protocols, which are all relevant to Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI). The discussion of information security protocols suggests that the paper may also belong to the category of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR). The paper also discusses the Hourglass model of Grid architecture, which is related to Software Engineering (cs.SE). Finally, the paper's focus on Global Grid Computing suggests that it may also belong to the category of Distributed Systems (cs.Distributed Systems).
